  "prompt": "Which digital circuit use by data bus to pass data from memory to register?",
  "response": "In digital circuits, a **data bus** is used to transfer data between components such as memory and registers. The specific circuits that utilize the data bus for this purpose typically include:\n\n1. **Multiplexer (MUX)**: A multiplexer can select data from multiple sources (like different memory locations or other registers) and route it to the output, which is connected to the data bus. This allows a single data bus to be shared among multiple devices.\n\n2. **Data Register**: A data register temporarily holds the data being transferred over the data bus. It can read data from memory or write data to memory based on the control signals.\n\n3. **Memory Address Decoder**: This circuit interprets the address lines to select which memory location is being accessed. It works in conjunction with the data bus to facilitate the data transfer process.\n\n4. **Bus Transceivers**: These are used to control the flow of data in and out of the data bus, allowing data to be sent and received by multiple devices on the bus.\n\n5. **Control Logic**: This manages the read and write operations on the data bus, determining when data flows from memory to a register or vice versa.\n\nIn more complex systems, such as microprocessors or microcontrollers, the integration of these components allows for efficient communication among different parts of the system, using the data bus as a central means of transferring data.",
